    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is It a Crime, Or a Hate Crime?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert A Fruge letter supports hate-crimes legislationr</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Tests of Fairness for Congress'' (editorial, Oct. 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Tests of Fairness for Congress'' (editorial, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>It is particularly disingenuous for some members of Congress, in arguing against hate-crimes legislation, to say that attacks on individuals are already a crime and that to distinguish assaults on special categories of people would create a bias that should not exist.</p>
        <p>Why does no one ever remind them that they themselves are protected by special laws that make attacks on members of Congress a federal offense? If they think they need added protection as a result of their special position, it stands to reason that some others might need the same.</p>
        <p>ROBERT A. FRUGE  Cathedral City, Calif., Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
